{{- /*
facts.tmpl — THE merged entry point for the named host-fact registry.

Emits a YAML map of every fact declared in .chezmoidata/facts.yaml
(factRegistry), which is where the names, types, probe layers, and fail-safe
directions are documented. Read it before touching this file.

  Consumers:
    templates / .chezmoiignore / deployed file content
      {{ $f := includeTemplate "facts.tmpl" . | fromYaml }}
      {{ if $f.nvidia }}…{{ end }}   {{ if eq $f.desktop "kde" }}…{{ end }}
    scripts                → .chezmoitemplates/facts-sh.tmpl  (FACT_* bash vars)
    gate-naming data files → .chezmoitemplates/facts-validate.tmpl

The map is assembled from two layers, and the split is by WHERE the probe can
run, not by cost — everything here is live:

  1. The CACHE — ${XDG_CACHE_HOME:-~/.cache}/chezmoi/facts.yaml, written by
     write_facts_cache in .install-prerequisites.sh, which chezmoi runs as its
     read-source-state.pre hook: once per chezmoi command, BEFORE the source
     state is read. Six facts live there because the template functions cannot
     express them — `output` turns a non-zero exit into a render-aborting
     template error (systemd-detect-virt --vm exits 1 on bare metal), and `glob`
     does not traverse symlinks, which /sys/bus/pci/devices/* is made of.
     NEVER probe a host fact with `output`.

  2. IN-PROCESS probes — a `stat`, a stat-guarded `include`, a `glob`, or a
     chezmoi builtin. No subprocess, so they cost nothing per render.

Two rules hold this file together:

  * EVERY absolute-path `include` is stat-guarded. `include` HARD-ERRORS on a
    missing file (`stat` merely returns nil), so an unguarded read of the cache
    or of /sys/class/dmi/ takes down every render on a host that lacks it —
    macOS and Windows in CI included.

  * A MISSING CACHE IS NOT AN ERROR. Every cached fact then resolves false,
    which is the conservative direction for all six (skip NVIDIA, skip Intel,
    skip the bare-metal set, skip ThinkPad/Studio, treat the host as a desktop).
    This is what makes the empty---config renders — the AGENTS.md stub-`op`
    recipe and the CI render-internals job, where the hook does not run at all —
    correct rather than merely non-fatal: the cache file persists on the host
    from the last REAL chezmoi command, and an absolute-path `include` reads it
    regardless of which config chezmoi was pointed at.
*/ -}}

{{- /* ---- Layer 1: the pre-hook cache ---------------------------------------
   Keep this path byte-identical to write_facts_cache's in the hook (and to
   Write-FactsCache in the .ps1). `env` reads the same XDG_CACHE_HOME the hook
   read, and .chezmoi.homeDir is the same $HOME — no `output` call needed. */ -}}
{{- $cacheHome := env "XDG_CACHE_HOME" -}}
{{- if eq $cacheHome "" -}}
{{-   $cacheHome = joinPath .chezmoi.homeDir ".cache" -}}
{{- end -}}
{{- $cachePath := joinPath $cacheHome "chezmoi" "facts.yaml" -}}
{{- /* SHAPE-CHECK THE RAW TEXT BEFORE fromYaml. `fromYaml` raises a TEMPLATE ERROR on
   malformed YAML, and a Go template has no recover — so a truncated or corrupt cache
   would abort the render of the root .chezmoiignore and take the whole tool down, not
   fall through to the defaults below. The `kindIs "map"` guard that used to sit here
   was dead code: fromYaml errors first, it never runs.

   The hook writes exactly one shape — comment lines, then `<name>: true|false` — so
   match that and parse nothing else. Anything unexpected is treated as no cache at
   all, which is the documented (and now actually reachable) fail-safe path. */ -}}
{{- $cached := dict -}}
{{- if stat $cachePath -}}
{{-   $raw := include $cachePath -}}
{{- /* `\r?` is load-bearing: the .ps1 half of the hook writes the cache through
   PowerShell, which line-ends with CRLF. `fromYaml` parses that fine — but a
   LF-only shape check silently rejects it, and every hook fact on Windows would
   fall back to its default forever. */ -}}
{{-   if regexMatch "^(#[^\r\n]*\r?\n|[A-Za-z][A-Za-z0-9]*: (true|false)\r?\n)+$" $raw -}}
{{-     $parsed := $raw | fromYaml -}}
{{-     if kindIs "map" $parsed -}}
{{-       $cached = $parsed -}}
{{-     end -}}
{{-   end -}}
{{- end -}}

{{- /* Cached facts are booleans. Coerce defensively: a missing key (no cache
   yet) and a non-boolean value (a truncated or hand-edited cache) both resolve
   false rather than leaking a string into a consumer's `if`. The next real
   chezmoi command rewrites the file before the render, so a damaged cache
   self-heals — no reason to fail the apply over it. */ -}}
{{- /* THE ABSENT-CACHE DEFAULT IS PER FACT, NOT A UNIFORM false — and getting that
   wrong is a fail-OPEN, which is why it is spelled out here rather than folded into
   one `default false`.

   The rule is: the value a fact takes when we DO NOT KNOW must be the one that
   SKIPS the thing it gates. For four of the six that is `false`, because the gate
   reads `<fact>` and false means skip:

     nvidia / intelGpu   skip the driver + CUDA / Intel graphics package sets
     ubuntuStudio        skip the pro-audio stack AND the realtime-limits drop-in
     vm                  skip etc/sudoers.d/* — the password-less-sudo drop-in.
                         THIS ONE IS A PRIVILEGE GRANT: `true` would install
                         `%wheel ALL=(ALL:ALL) NOPASSWD: ALL` on a host we cannot
                         identify. Never flip it.

   For the other two the gate is INVERTED — the fact being false is what makes the
   work happen — so the safe unknown value is `true`:

     virt      `bareMetalPackages` gates on `!virt`. A false default would install
               the bare-metal set (firmware, steam) inside a VM or container.
     headless  headless-guard SKIPS when the fact is 1. A false default would let a
               headless server run the whole desktop/system provisioning set that
               guard exists to keep off it.

   Both were caught in review as fail-open defaults. A future fact whose gate reads
   `!<fact>`, or whose guard skips on true, belongs in the `true` group — say so in
   its `whenFalse:` entry in .chezmoidata/facts.yaml.

   A non-boolean value (a truncated or hand-edited cache) takes the same safe
   default rather than leaking a string into a consumer's `if`; the next real
   chezmoi command rewrites the file before the render, so a damaged cache
   self-heals and there is no reason to fail the apply over it. */ -}}
{{- $absentDefault := dict
      "nvidia"       false
      "intelGpu"     false
      "ubuntuStudio" false
      "vm"           false
      "virt"         true
      "headless"     true -}}
{{- $facts := dict -}}
{{- range $name, $fallback := $absentDefault -}}
{{-   $value := index $cached $name -}}
{{-   if kindIs "bool" $value -}}
{{-     $_ := set $facts $name $value -}}
{{-   else -}}
{{-     $_ := set $facts $name $fallback -}}
{{-   end -}}
{{- end -}}

{{- /* ---- Layer 2a: chezmoi builtins ---------------------------------------- */ -}}
{{- $_ := set $facts "os" .chezmoi.os -}}
{{- $distro := "" -}}
{{- if and .chezmoi.osRelease (hasKey .chezmoi.osRelease "id") -}}
{{-   $distro = .chezmoi.osRelease.id -}}
{{- end -}}
{{- $_ := set $facts "distro" $distro -}}

{{- /* desktop — keyed on the shell binary the ISO shipped (stable from first
   boot; neither comes from this repo's package lists). KDE WINS when both are
   on PATH: that is today's precedence, since dot_config/.chezmoiignore drops the
   fcitx5 config only on a host with gnome-shell AND NOT plasmashell. With
   NEITHER (headless, container, CI) the value is `none`, and the file-content
   consumers fall back to their KDE variant — which is what keeps the CI
   artifacts deterministic and inert. */ -}}
{{- $desktop := "none" -}}
{{- if lookPath "plasmashell" -}}
{{-   $desktop = "kde" -}}
{{- else if lookPath "gnome-shell" -}}
{{-   $desktop = "gnome" -}}
{{- end -}}
{{- $_ := set $facts "desktop" $desktop -}}

{{- /* ---- Layer 2b: in-process file probes ---------------------------------- */ -}}

{{- /* thinkpad — the MODEL fields, not the vendor field. sys_vendor holds the
   manufacturer (LENOVO on every Lenovo consumer laptop, "Micro-Star
   International Co., Ltd." here) and never the string ThinkPad. product_version
   and product_family are the two fields the old `sudo dmidecode -t system` grep
   actually matched; reading them from /sys/class/dmi/id/ drops the sudo call. */ -}}
{{- $thinkpad := false -}}
{{- range $dmi := (list "/sys/class/dmi/id/product_version" "/sys/class/dmi/id/product_family") -}}
{{-   if stat $dmi -}}
{{-     if contains "thinkpad" (include $dmi | lower) -}}
{{-       $thinkpad = true -}}
{{-     end -}}
{{-   end -}}
{{- end -}}
{{- $_ := set $facts "thinkpad" $thinkpad -}}

{{- /* `stat` returns a MAP or nil, so it is used as a truthiness test and never
   compared with eq/ne — text/template's eq/ne reject a map operand outright
   ("incompatible types for comparison"), which would abort the render. */ -}}

{{- /* sddmBreeze — forcing Current=breeze without the theme installed yields a
   broken login screen, so the file that sets it ships only where this holds. */ -}}
{{- $sddmBreeze := false -}}
{{- if stat "/usr/share/sddm/themes/breeze/theme.conf" -}}
{{-   $sddmBreeze = true -}}
{{- end -}}
{{- $_ := set $facts "sddmBreeze" $sddmBreeze -}}

{{- /* gdm — probe the exact file-db the shipped /etc/dconf/profile/gdm
   references, not "is GNOME installed". */ -}}
{{- $gdm := false -}}
{{- if stat "/usr/share/gdm/greeter-dconf-defaults" -}}
{{-   $gdm = true -}}
{{- end -}}
{{- $_ := set $facts "gdm" $gdm -}}

{{- /* fprintdPam — pam_fprintd.so present AND a Debian-shaped common-auth. THE
   CONJUNCTION IS LOAD-BEARING: the second half is what keeps this repo's
   Debian-shaped /etc/pam.d/polkit-1 off Fedora, whose rpm-owned polkit-1
   @includes system-auth. Drop it and a Fedora apply overwrites that file with a
   stack referencing a file Fedora does not have — breaking every polkit prompt.
   Both multiarch security dirs are globbed, mirroring has_pam_fprintd() in
   install-system-10-files. */ -}}
{{- $fprintdPam := false -}}
{{- if stat "/etc/pam.d/common-auth" -}}
{{-   range $pattern := (list "/usr/lib/*/security/pam_fprintd.so" "/lib/*/security/pam_fprintd.so") -}}
{{-     if glob $pattern -}}
{{-       $fprintdPam = true -}}
{{-     end -}}
{{-   end -}}
{{- end -}}
{{- $_ := set $facts "fprintdPam" $fprintdPam -}}

{{- /* container — a Podman/Docker marker WITHOUT the toolbox marker. distrobox
   and toolbox both bind-mount the host $HOME and both create /run/.toolboxenv, so
   an apply inside one targets the REAL $HOME and must provision like a host. Keep
   this predicate byte-identical to the root .chezmoiignore's, or the ignore set
   and the fact will disagree about the same machine. */ -}}
{{- $container := false -}}
{{- if or (stat "/run/.containerenv") (stat "/.dockerenv") -}}
{{-   if not (stat "/run/.toolboxenv") -}}
{{-     $container = true -}}
{{-   end -}}
{{- end -}}
{{- $_ := set $facts "container" $container -}}

{{- /* toYaml sorts the keys, so the emitted map is deterministic — which is what
   lets facts-sh.tmpl and the CI artifacts be diffed. */ -}}
{{ $facts | toYaml }}
